07250nam a22007215i 9780773555679DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735556797 a10.1515/97807735556792doi  a(DE-B1597)654767  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a971.3/0422300aDivided Province :bOntario Politics in the Age of Neoliberalism /ced. by Greg Albo, Bryan M. Evans. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b26 tables, 17 figures, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables, Figures, and Maps -- tPreface -- tDivided Province: Democracy and the Politics of State Restructuring in Ontario -- tThe Political Economy of Neoliberalism in Ontario -- tThe Ontario Growth Model: The “End of the Road” or a “New Economy”? -- tThe Geography of the Ontario Service Economy -- tA Neoliberal Pause? The Auto and Manufacturing Sectors in Ontario since Free Trade -- tNorthern Ontario and the Crisis of Development and Democracy -- tTransforming the Ontario State -- tNew bargains? Ontario and Federalism in the Neoliberal Period -- tGendering the State: Women and Public Policy in Ontario -- tMunicipal Neoliberalism and the Ontario State -- tClass, Power, and Neoliberal Employment Policy -- tConsolidating the Neoliberal Policy Regime in Ontario -- tPoverty Policy in Ontario: you Can’t Eat Good Intentions -- tReforming Health Services in Ontario: Contradictions -- tCompeting Policy Paradigms and the Search for Sustainability in Ontario Electricity Policy -- tSchooling Goes to Market: The Consolidation of Lean Education in Ontario -- tDemocratic Politics and Social Movements -- tColonialism, Indigenous Struggles, and the Ontario state -- tUnequal Futures: Race and Class under Neoliberalism in Ontario -- tThe Democratic Imagination in Ontario and Participatory Budgeting -- tThe Challenges of Union Political Action in the Era of Neoliberalism -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo government jurisdiction in Canada has so radically transformed its public policies over the past decades as Ontario, and yet the province has also maintained a striking degree of political stability in its party system. Since the 1990s, neoliberalism has been the point of reference in constructing policy agendas for all of Ontario's political parties. It has guided the strategy for governance of the dominant Liberal Party since 2003, even as it divides the province between workers and employers, north and south, rural and urban, and racialized minorities and the majority population. With a focus on the governments of Mike Harris, Dalton McGuinty, and Kathleen Wynne, Divided Province brings together leading researchers to dissect the province's public policies since the 1990s. Presenting original, state-of-the-art research, the book demonstrates that, although the Conservative government of Mike Harris implemented the sharpest and most profound shift towards the establishment of a neoliberal regime in the province, the subsequent Liberal governments consolidated that neoliberal turn. The essays in this volume explore the consequences of this ideological turn across a spectrum of policies, including health, education, poverty, energy, employment, manufacturing, and how it has impacted workers, women, First Nations, and other distinct communities. The first book to offer a comprehensive critical account of neoliberalism in Ontario, Divided Province overturns conventional readings of the province's politics and suggests that building a more democratic and egalitarian alternative to the current orthodoxy requires nothing less than a radical rupture from existing policies and political alliances. Without such a decisive break, political space may well open up again for the populist right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNeoliberalismzOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 0aNeoliberalismzOntarioxHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAlbo, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbo, Greg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnastakis, Dimitry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairns, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrummond, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Bryan M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFanelli, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFindlay, Tammy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalabuzi, Grace-Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraefe, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Carol-Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeadbeater, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacwhirter, Winfield, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaley, Terry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeters, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSears, 